(24, '10 Possible Reasons Why Your Site Is Not Indexed by Google', 'general.jpg', '<p>Nothing is more devastating for a webmaster than to realize that his/her website''s pages are not indexed on Google. This is as good as their web pages being non-existent! Integral to the success of a web based business or even a non-commercial website is the amount of organic traffic it can muster up through the best search engines (read Google).</p>\r\n<p><!-- pagebreak --></p>\r\n<p>Pre-requisite to even appearing on Google search results for your targeted keywords is being visible to Google''s web crawlers. Simply put, indexing is what Google does to find out websites that can feature in its search results. Imagine the loss it''s going to be for your web store, blog, and web portals if they cease to exist for Google!</p>\r\n<h2>How to find if your web pages are not being indexed?</h2>\r\n<p>The simplest trick is to conduct a quick Google search by typing in <em>site:yoursite.com, </em>where ''yoursite'' is replaced with the name of your website. Next, observe the number of search results it shows, and compare the number with the actual number of pages of your website. Since Google''s search results give a ballpark estimate, it''s alright if you don''t get an exact match in the numbers. However, a substantial difference is a cause for concern, and observation of the same should be followed by a thorough check. In most cases, if you see a vast difference, or if you don''t even get a result, it''s time to see why Google is not indexing your website properly.</p>\r\n<h2>What to do when Google doesn''t index your website?</h2>\r\n<p>The first step you must take, bypassing every other tip or trick given to you by any web wizard, is to check out your admin panel in Google Webmasters Tools. It is easy to spot the common problems with websites that render Google unable to crawl or index them. Of course, there could well be cases wherein everything will look perfect shape with your Google Webmasters Tools dashboard. There are several common reasons that cut websites off from Google''s indexing efforts. Here, we discuss 10 of the commonest of these reasons, and their solutions.</p>\r\n<h3>Your website is too new to be found yet!</h3>\r\n<p>New webmasters often find their websites missing from Google''s expected search results. Ideally, it makes sense to wait a day after you publish your website for it to be indexed on Google. If you still can''t find it, check whether the sitemap is correctly created and successfully submitted to the search engine. Also, you might need to request Google to fetch your website, which will involve logging into Google Webmasters Tools and following some simple steps.</p>\r\n<h3>The domain is banned by Google!</h3>\r\n<p>Google has been constantly upgrading its search algorithms, and is proactive in penalizing websites that do not abide by its principles or best practices. In most cases, a Google penalty is in the form of a decrease in the ranking of a website. However, there are cases of severe violation of Google''s webmasters guidelines that result in complete removal of a website from Google''s index! In such cases, Google sends a notification of website de-indexing to the webmaster. So, unless you''ve had a specific notification from Google, you can assume that the de-indexing is because of any of the other reasons. Also, remember to follow the best practices of website traffic building.</p>\r\n<h3>The robots.txt file is blocking the website or parts of it</h3>\r\n<p>Robots.txt file is used by website developers to mark out portions of the website that are not intended to be indexed. It can happen that a developer can block out the entire website or some unintended part of it by mistake. The simple fix is to check the robots.txt file and remove the relevant entries from it.</p>\r\n<h3>Google is failing to crawl your webpages</h3>\r\n<p>In several cases, webpages are found to be de-indexed just because Google''s crawlers are unable to crawl them. To identify such crawling errors, go to Google Webmaster Tools and find out the ''Crawl Errors'' by selecting your website and clicking on ''Crawl''. You will be shown the pages with the error, if there are any.</p>\r\n<h3>Lots of duplicate content on your website</h3>\r\n<p>In many ways, Google''s crawlers can give up attempts of crawling your website if there is too much duplication of content there. Multiple URL''s pointing to same content can force Google to give up attempting to crawl your website, or de-index it. The best solution in such a scenario is to identify the duplicate URLs and make them redirect to the parent link. Also, canonicalization of pages could serve your purpose, but it comes with the flipside that Google has been known to have de-indexed websites with confused canonicalization.</p>\r\n<h3>Hosting problems - server failure, slow download speed</h3>\r\n<p>Does your website take forever to load? If so, it''s highly likely that Google''s crawlers will not crawl your website. Also, if your hosting provider experiences frequent server downtimes, your website runs the risk of being de-indexed. Crawlers will not access what they can''t access, as simple as that. Hosting problems and slow downloading speeds can kill your website even if they manage to get crawled, so avoid these issues at all costs.</p>\r\n<h3>Troubles with settings in terms of AJAX and Javascript</h3>\r\n<p>Google can skip indexing of pages with AJAX and JavaScript. These web development languages are not too easily indexed by Google crawlers. So, if your pages are incorrectly configured in terms of AJX and JavaScript, then Google can skip the pages. So, for AJAX and Javascript intensive web-pages, be very careful about the configuration.</p>\r\n<h3>No-index meta tag used to block website</h3>\r\n<p>Webmasters, or web designers, have control over elements of their websites that they don''t want to be indexed. No-index meta tags are used for this purpose. An example of the same is &ndash;</p>\r\n<p>&lt;META NAME=&rdquo;ROBOTS&rdquo; CONTENT=&rdquo;NOINDEX, NOFOLLOW&rdquo;&gt;</p>\r\n<p>Such a line of code, if present in the home page''s code, can cause the website to be de-indexed as the crawlers consider the meta tags as a request for not indexing the website! The simple solution &ndash; remove the piece of code with the statement similar to above.</p>\r\n<h3>Site is closed for indexation in .htcaccess file</h3>\r\n<p>Simply put, the ,htaccess is a part of the way the website exists on a server, and is instrumental in making the website available for access on the global internet network. Written in Apache, the .htaccess files can be used to block crawlers, and can hence be the unintended reason of a website being ignored by Google''s bots.</p>\r\n<h3>Visibility for search engines switched off in WordPress</h3>\r\n<p>If you''re using Wordpress for publishing your web content, your website could fall into the dark nether space of non-existence if you fail to switch the privacy settings on. The path is &ndash; Admin &gt; Settings &gt; Privacy to Check. Just ensure the simple step, it could be the difference between the indexing and ignoring of your website by Google''s crawlers.</p>', '', '', '', 0, 'This article will help you to find out why your website isn''t indexed by Google.', 'Google, indexing, SEO', '10-possible-reasons-why-your-site-is-not-indexed-by-Google', 482, '2015-10-03 16:00:21', 1, 1),
(25, 'How to get under the Google filters with a 100% guarantee?', 'general.jpg', '<p>Yep, you haven''t misheard : "How to get under the Google filters with a 100% guarantee". There are hundreds of tips and articles about how NOT to get under the Google Penguin and Google Panda, however it doesn''t enlighten most SEO marketers and that''s why we decided to describe how can you actually get your site chased by Google filters. You can be sure that those methods were tested and they work. So, if we are going to ditch a website, we are positive to use them. If not - we don''t want to be under Google filters, we act vice versa.</p>\r\n<p><!-- pagebreak --></p>\r\n<h2>1. Get a free SEO content.</h2>\r\n<p>We can start with the most practical way to easily get SEO content in couple minutes. Let''s imagine an ordinary situation, we don''t have much time to write some unique content or think it''s just lame (let those who don''t have anything important happening do it). Find in Google some sites with a similar theme, copy a text from the main page (as well as from any other pages) and place it on your personal website. Here you go!.. almost done. Just some small steps to do and you''ll get an excellent content, even better than the original. Simply stuff the stolen content with keywords that drive your site. Put keywords in different parts of the text, so that they appear everywhere.</p>\r\n<h2>2. And now the links.</h2>\r\n<p>A lot of links. Enormous amounts of links. Remember, the more links you have, the better. But having lots of links doesn''t mean having huge expenses. Here''s the secret how to really get thousands of links quickly and for pennies. Go to Digitalpoint Forum and in the buy section create a topic "Looking for tons of cool and cheap links". In couple minutes you''ll receive dozens of letters that will offer you to purchase thousands of cheap links in bulk. Moreover, I recommend you to point your email in Threads on forum and you''ll get thousands of emails with the attached Excel files from grateful Indian marketers. So buy links in large batches - a lot and straightway. Especially if your site is new, it''s better to buy thousands of links at once, thus you''ll get a lot of traffic and your site will go up in searching results. Listen to no one - the attendance and the reputation of donors is a myth. Keep to the main thing - the amount of links, because there''s almost no difference whether will or will not the site for placing a link be trusted.</p>\r\n<h2>3. But what about the anchors?</h2>\r\n<p>Anchor texts can be a very important moment for the SEO promotion of your site. Choose some relevant to your website keywords, it will be better if their amount will be up to 5, not more. Use those anchors in all your links. Don''t use unoriginal or brand links - they are useless. If we aim to promote site due to particular keywords, than those keywords are to be in the links. Another important hint - nofollow links are of no use for us, we need only dofollow links.</p>\r\n<h2>4. Relevance of the donor-sites.</h2>\r\n<p>I''ll be honest - I won''t even bother with that. It is very hard to find relevant websites, especially trustworthy. And the cost of such links will be high. That''s why don''t waste your time and money and simply buy links in bulk as I''ve already mentioned above.</p>\r\n<h2>5. Should you get permanent links?</h2>\r\n<p>Under no circumstances! It is absolutely meaningless. Permanent links will cost a lot more than those for a limited time. The money saved can be more effectively used on purchasing more links in bulk. Buy for a month or two. Afterwards, if necessary, you can prolong them. The most important, I''m repeating again, place as many links on the website as possible. Don''t let it bother you that they will disappear in some time. Google is totally okay if links disappear. It even seems more natural for him.</p>\r\n<h2>6. Sell links by yourself.</h2>\r\n<p>In order to compensate some expenses on buying links I recommend to sell links by yourself. You ask how other webmasters find out that your site is selling links? Very simply - place an ad in side wide block that you sell links on this site. Come in handy can also be registration on the links exchange and set selling links automatically.</p>\r\n<h2>7. Engage in link exchange networks.</h2>\r\n<p>Another excellent way to promote your website is to use the variety of links exchange networks. As in case of trading links it is useful to customize an automatic exchange. This will save your time.</p>\r\n<h2>8. Use thousands of web directories.</h2>\r\n<p>Web directories are still totally appropriate for SEO. The main thing is to have as much directories as possible. Order on the same forum a submit for thousands of directories. I''ve seen offers of 10k free directories for only $150-200. Don''t be afraid to use such services. The description for directories should be the same. The best is to simply to copy it from your own website. When choosing the anchor determine the most important keyword for you and use it for all directories. Be focused on what is important.</p>\r\n<h2>9. Web 2.0 Sites</h2>\r\n<p>This is a very efficient method for getting high quality links, and besides it''s absolutely free. Register in popular blog platforms. Create one page websites by using those builders. The content for this site we prepare in the same way as we did previously for our site (read point 1). Each Web 2.0 page should refer to your site and to itself as well. The more such sites you build the better.</p>\r\n<h2>10. Article Marketing</h2>\r\n<p>The old school way that is still appropriate for Google. Write one article and place it in article directories. You''ll get better results if you use automatic submission services in article directories. Thus you''ll get a lot of links in a short time. And don''t forget to place some links to your site in the article, make it 5-10 on different pages of your website. As usually, use solely business anchors.</p>\r\n<p>I hope those methods will be useful for you. I recommend to use them entirely together in order to increase the chances of your website to get under the Google filters. If you aren''t willing to suffer the Google sanctions do everything vice versa and may the force be with you!</p>', '', '', '', 0, 'Yep, you haven''t misheard : "How to get under the Google filters with a 100% guarantee?". There are hundreds of tips and articles about how NOT to get under the Google Penguin and Google Panda, however it doesn''t enlighten most SEO marketers...', 'Google filters, Google Penguin, Google Panda, SEO', 'how-to-get-under-the-google-filters', 447, '2015-10-05 23:32:16', 0, 1),
(26, 'How does Google Panda work? How to avoid its sanctions?', 'panda general.jpg', '<h2>Google Panda &ndash; what''s this?</h2>\r\n<p>Never heard of Google Panda? Is it an all new Google product? A mascot panda for the web giant? A secret society devising means to hack Google users'' personal details? Well, Google Panda is nothing out of these. Let''s start with the basics; Google is a search engine built upon the values of simplicity and relevance, and is dedicated to providing the best possible web content results to users in response to searches made using the search engine. What logically follows is Google''s maniac dedication towards not letting low quality content find its way to the top of its search results and that''s why it continues to revamp, reinvent and improve the algorithms it uses to filter out and present web content. Google Panda is the cute sounding yet no-nonsense and revolutionary search algorithm update affected on 24 February 2011, aimed at reducing the web ranking of low quality websites that provide worthless and copied content, are dotted with irrelevant advertisements and are not useful for readers and viewers in general. At the same time as it tries to penalize low quality and useless websites, Google Panda is also about providing better rankings to top quality websites that present well researched and original content with reports, analyses and more. However, it might not be wrong to take more than a single viewpoint on what Google Panda actually is. Here are three ways to look at it:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>An algorithm update</strong> - Purely based on the number of websites that experienced considerable changes in their original rankings after the Panda update, it''s fairly justifiable to call it an out and out algorithm update.</li>\r\n<li><strong>A temporary penalty</strong> - Despite the fact that the Panda update was severe on thousands of websites, it also allowed them to cover the lost ground by correcting the mistakes that Panda is designed to penalize, which makes Panda a temporary penalty doled out on defaulting websites</li>\r\n<li><strong>An all new ranking factor</strong> - A website''s Panda Score is instrumental in deciding as to where its web pages are ranked, and this makes Panda stand in the light of ranking factors such as PageRank and Meta Tags.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Google''s Panda update is meant to target web pages that are low in quality, although they might not be spam. Before Panda did the clean up act, it was a common strategy for webmasters to publish several low quality articles that were mindlessly stuffed with keywords, to content farms. In fact, webmasters used to submit these low quality articles to several content farms to increase their backlinks, at the cost of Google''s search results'' quality and worth. Panda went after thin content and made sure that such useless websites with very little originality were penalized. The Panda penalty is site-wide and affects the entire website if enough web pages are deemed useless by Panda. Also, Panda made sure that websites that just copied their content from other websites were not able to outrank the original creators of the content. No wonders it was launched with the name of Farmer, because of its clean up jobs on content farms!</p>\r\n<h2>How does Google Panda work?</h2>\r\n<p>Of course, there will never be 100 percent information available in the public domain about the intricacies of how Google Panda works, there is still enough known to satiate inquisitive webmasters. Panda is an algorithm based on heuristics that doesn''t depend on too many complex calculations and instead tries to categorize websites into categories such as ''low quality'' and ''high quality'' after allotting their web pages a score known as the Panda Score. Now, this score depends on several quality attributes with their different weights, and this selection of these attributes with their weights is what Google''s engineers would have done after diligent analyses and studies of hundreds or thousands of websites. So, once a website''s web pages are allotted Panda scores, the cumulative impact on the website could be a decrease or increase in its ranking. Since the selections of quality attributes and their weights in order to calculate the Panda Score are always improving, we have already seen several updates to the Panda algorithm and can expect the same from the future as well.</p>\r\n<p>In more practical terms, Google Panda''s working is best understood in terms of identifying the website aspects it evaluates. Among the most integral of these are:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>Originality of content</strong>- Websites that copy content from multiple sources and pack their web pages with what seems like really worthwhile content are at the receiving end with Panda, and that''s because of the prime importance of original content. Content duplication is severely dealt with by Panda, whereas original content with reports, tables and analyses is rewarded.</li>\r\n<li><strong>Substantiality of content </strong>&ndash; Panda does not go well with websites that have many web pages but not much content on the pages. Websites with just a few lines of mediocre content on their pages end up in the bad books of Panda and are penalized.</li>\r\n<li><strong>Worth of content</strong> &ndash; How does Panda successfully make out worthwhile content from merely copywriter quality content? It uses parameters such as author authority and website''s credibility to adjudge upon the same, and ensures that informative and worthwhile content laden web pages get better Panda scores.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Apart from all these, there are other deficiencies that Google Panda identifies and penalizes. Web pages with loads of advertisements creating a chaos and the ones with thoughtless and reckless designing are not really appreciated by Panda. Also, web pages that are not updated for long times are penalized, as are websites that index useless pages on Google.</p>\r\n<h2>Which errors on a website will cause to sanctions of Google Panda?</h2>\r\n<p>Good, bad, evil or cute - Google Panda is here to say, and considering indications from Google, it''s going to be a vital cog in Google''s search engine experience improvement drive for the future. So, nothing is more important than identifying as to what invites the fury of Google Panda for webmasters. It''s after diligent analyses of websites that have gone down after Panda updates and the possible content and quality deficiencies they suffered from that a suggestive list of aspects that can be serious reasons of Panda sanctions has come up. Here''s more on all that does not go well with Panda.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Thin content</strong> &ndash; You''ve heard it before, but it makes all the sense to hear it again. Among Panda''s most obvious victims are websites that have loads of web pages but not much content on them. Such websites often inflate themselves with advertisement pages and thin content pages, which leave users wanting for more. Google wants its users to be served only really useful web results, and that''s why it chases away thin content websites.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Compromised content to chase keywords</strong> &ndash; How irritating is it for you to surf a website that is laden with web pages links that seem useful, but only serve the same content over and over, with minor keyword variations. This irritates Panda no ends! Webmasters often compromise website quality to be able to target keywords with minor variations.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Duplication is a sin</strong> &ndash; Content duplication is a certain turn down for Google Panda. Whether you copy content from your own web pages to other pages, or copy anybody''s content to use on your website, Panda will be tough on your website. Even if you''re providing multiple pages with remarkably similar content in the form of printer-friendly, single-page (instead of multi-page article), or stripped down pages targeting mobile devices, Panda will identify and correspondingly penalize you, unless you no-index these similar content pages. Dynamically generated URLs pointing to the same source URL need to be accompanied by Rel=''Canonocal'' tag for Google to not treat them as deliberate attempts to duplicate pages.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Ad laden websites</strong> &ndash; Panda has cracked down on websites that serve a lot of advertisements to users. In fact, among the prominent traffic losers after Panda updates are websites that make readers scroll down through rivers of advertisements before serving them any useful content. <strong>Even irrelevant and excessive banner ads are deemed to be hindering to a decent user experience, and are hence penalized by Panda. </strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>Empty web pages and redundant URLs</strong> &ndash; Whether it''s a housekeeping mistake on the part of webmasters or a deliberate attempt to fool viewers into believing that the website is content rich and expansive, URL duplication and empty web pages are a strict NO NO with Google Panda. Even if empty web pages result from the internal search functionality of the website, Panda slaps penalties.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Purchased links instead of earned links</strong> &ndash; No longer are the rich webmasters able to buy link-backs in order to secure better SERPs with Google. Panda is smart enough to identify backlinks from shady sources, and is quick in penalizing the websites that are identified for using black hat and cheap link buying techniques.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Housekeeping mistakes that make your websites suffer </strong>&ndash; Google Panda update has always been tough on websites that suffer from deliberate or unintentional housekeeping errors that make the users experience a messy one. Among the most obvious lessons for webmasters are:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Panda assumes that your websites are either hosting spam or not doing anything to prevent spam when it finds a considerable proportion of irrelevant outgoing links on your web pages.</li>\r\n<li>Unless you use robots.txt to point out that search results are not meant to be indexed, Google treats the same as an attempt to duplicate content and hence levies appropriate penalties on your website''s Panda Score.</li>\r\n<li>Improper internal linking makes your website suffer, so avoid multiple links pointing to the same pages, whether intentional or not.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><span style="font-size: xx-small;">Image cortesy <a href="https://www.pinterest.com/dnvillanueva/" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">Dn Villanueva</a></span></p>', '', '', '', 0, 'Google Panda – what’s this? Never heard of Google Panda? Is it an all new Google product? A mascot panda for the web giant? A secret society devising means to hack Google users'' personal details? Well, Google Panda is nothing out of these. Let''s start wit', 'Google filters, Google Panda, SEO', 'how-does-google-panda-work', 399, '2015-10-12 20:47:28', 1, 1),
(27, '25 Best Web Directories for SEO', 'general.jpg', '<p>SEO is on every webmaster''s mind; truly, a website is as good as nothing without the life and soul of SEO. It makes sense to do as much as possible in terms of affecting a diversified SEO strategy, as you can truly never know as to what is the perfect formula of SEO success. Web directories have been, and continue, to be an appreciable portion of both traditional and more dynamic webmasters and SEO experts, and that''s in spite of the fact that with the updating Google search algorithms, the real SEO impact of web directories has been mitigated to a certain extent. It was not long ago when web directory submissions contributed to your backlink profiles, enabled you to rank for more keywords, generate organic traffic for your websites, and get easily and quickly crawled. Of course, it''s not as incontestable a proposition at this date, but that does not completely obscure the contributions that web directories have to make to the SEO appeal of your website.</p>\r\n<p>There''s every reason for you to filter out authoritative and renowned web directories that have stood like oaks and weathered the tests of time. Submissions to these directories are guaranteed to catalyze great SEO results for your websites, apart from increasing the traffic inflow because of the number of readers of these directories'' articles. Several factors count when you try to judge a web directory, some of them being:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>Authority</strong> &ndash; Is it a niche web directory, with authority in a domain?</li>\r\n<li><strong>Popularity</strong> &ndash; How many monthly visitors does the directly record? What''s the number of registered members?</li>\r\n<li><strong>Age</strong> &ndash; Has the directory been present in the market long enough? Is it constantly upgrading?</li>\r\n<li><strong>Number of pages indexed by Google</strong> &ndash; This one''s a really integral parameter. Does the directory enjoy a substantial number of indexed pages with Google or any other search engine you''re specifically targeting?</li>\r\n<li><strong>Page Rank</strong> &ndash; What''s the PR of the web directory? High PR generally means that getting on to the directory could be tough for you!</li>\r\n<li><strong>Ratings and stats</strong> &ndash; How do Alexa or other reputed web reputation and statistics agencies rate and regard the web directory?</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>We save you all the research efforts and present an exhaustive list of 25 of the most worthwhile, credible and empowered web directories from the cyber-sphere. Target the most relevant ones from these and give impetus to your SEO efforts.</p>\r\n<h2>1. <a href="http://www.dmoz.org/" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">DMOZ</a></h2>\r\n<p>DMOZ, established around 1999, is easily among the most populous web directories, and is maintained by volunteer editors from across the globe. With a thoroughly organized web structure, dozens of main categories and niche categories, and estimated 3.5 million traffic count, DMOZ is a good investment of your web directory submission efforts. The best part - you don''t have to pay anything to be a part of this revered web directory.</p>\r\n<h2>2. <a href="https://dir.yahoo.com/" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">Yahoo Directory</a></h2>\r\n<p>Yahoo has been the premier online directory for near two decades now, being established in 1995. With a worldwide presence, an iconic image and a credible database, the directory receives near 1.6 million visitors every month, with an average viewing time of at least 2 minutes. And it costs absolutely nothing to get enlisted with the directory as well.</p>\r\n<h2>3. <a href="http://www.dirjournal.com/" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">Directory Journal</a></h2>\r\n<p>Direct Journal, though relatively new on the block, has quickly gained favor throughout world for being one of the most trust web directories. With over 80 K visits per month, the site receives decent amount of focused traffic to its listings. Getting listed in the directory costs $60 per month, but the rewards in return in are nevertheless remarkable.</p>\r\n<h2>4. <a href="http://www.joeant.com/" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">JoeAnt</a></h2>\r\n<p>Established in the wake of the new millennium, JoeAnt is a popular volunteer maintained web directory with a massive web presence. With a constant traffic flow nearing 80k, the site receives a high SEO score from all web experts. The volunteer based indexing means, most URLs may have already been listed, or else you can join for free with no hidden costs.</p>\r\n<h2>5. <a href="http://www.avivadirectory.com/" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">Aviva Directory</a></h2>\r\n<p>Started in 2005, Aviva Directory lists websites and blogs separately based on a broad range of categories making navigation through them simple. With a steady traffic of 70k visitors per month, the directory receives periodic updates of revisions to the index. Completely managed and maintained by professional staff, the directory charges $50 for as annual listing fee per URL.</p>\r\n<h2>6. <a href="http://www.scrubtheweb.com/" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">Scrubtheweb</a></h2>\r\n<p>Scrubthweb has been the go-to directory for most website owners, thanks to the highly interactive navigation options and the excellent SEO tools provided by the index. Created in 1995, the directly receives over 400k hits each month. And the best part is, the directory charges nothing to add a URL to the index.</p>\r\n<h2>7. <a href="http://www.directoryworld.net" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">Directory World</a></h2>\r\n<p>With its simple and easy-to-navigate design, Directory World is the ideal human edited directory. With a number of focused niche categories and an estimated traffic inflow of 60k visitors, the index is sure the right place to update your URL. And the best thing is, reviews and additions of web address cost nothing for the user.</p>\r\n<h2>8. <a href="http://www.jayde.com" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">Jayde</a></h2>\r\n<p>Jayde prides itself as a business to business web directory with special focus on business related search listings. Created in 1996, it is one of the oldest web listings online, and has always remained free to use for users. The directory receives over 410K visits each month with an average page time of over 4 minutes.</p>\r\n<h2>9. <a href="http://botw.org" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">Best of the Web</a></h2>\r\n<p>Best of the Web seamlessly integrates social network sites with its listings to increase the visibility of any site included in its directory, making it one of the best directories to submit your site to. Established in 1994, the directory receives a constant traffic of over 310K visitors each month. The directory charges $149.95 for a listing and review.</p>\r\n<h2>10. <a href="http://www.cannylink.com/" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">Cannylink</a></h2>\r\n<p>During the time of its creation, in 1997, Cannylink was the largest hand coded directory which renders it superior human navigation features. The directory includes target specific categories, and elaborate sublists, and receives over 20K visits per month. The minimal listing charge is priced $19.95 for an unlimited time, this includes review by the editorial board as well.</p>\r\n<h2>11. <a href="http://www.stpt.com/directory" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">Starting Point</a></h2>\r\n<p>With profession specific listings, Starting Point is the best directory for submitting sites related to specific businesses or professions. Started in 1995, the directory offers an ad-free clean interface for quick search and easy location. With a steady traffic flow of 10K, the site assures guaranteed views of relevant URLs. The listing at the directory is priced at $99 per year.</p>\r\n<h2>12. <a href="http://www.elib.org/" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">Elib</a></h2>\r\n<p>Dedicated exclusively for listing shopping and ecommerce websites, Elib is a specialty directory that ensures more targeted traffic to your site. Created in 2003, the directory receives over 10000 visitors each month. The broader search regions, specific category wise ecommerce listing, and a charge free indexing, make it ideal for e-shop owners.</p>\r\n<h2>13. <a href="http://www.directory.v7n.com/" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">Directory@v7n</a></h2>\r\n<p>Directory@v7n, established in 2004, is one of the most sought after directories in the US and receives over 10000 visitors each month. Featuring region specific and city specific listing, the directory is ideal for local business and vendors. The directory charges a one time amount of $49.95 for each URL submission.</p>\r\n<h2>14. <a href="http://www.gimpsy.com/" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">Gimpsy</a></h2>\r\n<p>Launched in the year 2001, Gimpsy is an editor reviewed online web directory with a global presence and a diverse viewership. With a neat action based search menu, the directory links to related categories for a particular activity automatically. With a steady 25K viewership, and cost free membership the web directory is truly a bargain.</p>\r\n<h2>15. <a href="http://www.goguides.org/" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">Go Guides</a></h2>\r\n<p>With a peer reviewed database, and a completely spam free listing, the Go Guides web register ranks high when it comes to providing credible web information. Created in 2001, the directory is one of the oldest and popular indexing sites on the web, with an average 30K viewership per month. The directory costs $69.95 per review and addition of URL.</p>\r\n<h2>16. <a href="http://www.alivedirectory.com/" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">Alive Directory</a></h2>\r\n<p>Consistent ranked high by popular SEO consultants, the Alive Directory offers a clean and simple-to-use web indexing services. With close to a decade''s web presence, the directory receives 20k hits each month, and boasts a minimal bounce rate. The listing costs $ 49.95 for addition of single registered link, and offers money back guarantee as well.</p>\r\n<h2>17. <a href="http://www.webworldindex.com" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">Web World Index</a></h2>\r\n<p>With both professional and region centric listing, Web World Index is the most searched register for local and region web addresses. Established in 2001, the site''s popularity is undisputed and on average receives 110K visitors from all over the world. Submission of URLs regional categories is absolutely free with the web directory.</p>\r\n<h2>18. <a href="http://www.01webdirectory.com" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">01 web directory</a></h2>\r\n<p>01 Web Directory, since its inception in 2003, has been the go-to index for spam free, reviewed web listings. With separate sections for website and blogs, and features to add powerful SEO and marketing tools, the index offers the best bargain at just $49 per listing. And with an average traffic inflow of 110K visitors your website is sure to find its place.</p>\r\n<h2>19. <a href="http://www.ipl.org" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">IPL</a></h2>\r\n<p>Launched in year 1997, IPL is a massive volunteer maintained online web directory, which partners with professionals and researchers from around the world. With over 650K hits each month, it''s one of the most popular web indexes and has completely categorized sections for every user. The best thing about the directory is that it costs absolutely nothing to submit a listing.</p>\r\n<h2>20. <a href="http://www.mastermoz.com" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">Mastermoz</a></h2>\r\n<p>With complete social integration and a diverse web viewership, Mastermoz ensures targeted traffic flow to your website. The directory has been around since 2004, and receives a constant monthly traffic of 50K visitors, thanks to its spam free indexing and easy to navigate categories. The annual submission cost for a single URL costs $19.95 with the directory.</p>\r\n<h2>21. <a href="http://www.linkpedia.net" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">Linkpedia</a></h2>\r\n<p>Relatively new on the block, Linkpedia still ensures a complete return on investment with its advance indexing functionalities and large viewer base. With neatly categorized links and business specific listing, the directory receives over 60K targeted traffic each month. And the best part is, the directory charges nothing for submitting regular URLs to its listings.</p>\r\n<h2>22. <a href="https://www.somuch.com" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">Somuch</a></h2>\r\n<p>Somuch, founded in 1997, is one of the premier indexing services of the web with a true worldwide presence. With an average traffic flow of over 310,000 visitors every month, the directory receives the largest focused traffic compared any other indexing site. Since the site is largely volunteer maintained, it costs nothing to submit a link to the registry.</p>\r\n<h2>23. <a href="http://www.rdirectory.net" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">Rdirectory</a></h2>\r\n<p>Rdirectory has been around since 2005, and is ranked one of the top web directories by users around the world. With its highly subcategorized listings and sparsely populated pages, it attracts over 95,000 visitors each month. And the direct links to websites and genuine backlinks help with SEO as well. The registry costs no money for submitting regular URLs to be reviewed.</p>\r\n<h2>24. <a href="http://www.amray.com" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">Amray</a></h2>\r\n<p>Considered as the most popular free web directory, Amray charges nothing from users for reviewing and listing URLs. With an average 40K traffic flow, the directory maintains a decent inflow of targeted visitors as well. The business specific indexing and the quick navigation options ensure guaranteed traffic to your site.</p>\r\n<h2>25. <a href="http://www.prolinkdirectory.com" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">Prolinkdirectory</a></h2>\r\n<p>Prolinkdirectory, established in 2000, is one of the oldest web indexing services with a large volume traffic flow. Attracting over 160K hits each month, the directory is a great bargain considering it charges nothing for its listings. The directory also has separate categorized pages for website links, blogs and article pages.</p>', '', '', '', 0, 'We save you all the research efforts and present an exhaustive list of 25 of the most worthwhile, credible and empowered web directories from the cyber-sphere.', 'best web directories, Top directories, directory, DMOZ, yahoo directory, Directory Journal, JoeAnt, Aviva Directory, Scrubtheweb, Directory World, Jayde, Best of the Web, Cannylink, Starting Point, Elib, Directory@v7n, Gimpsy, Go Guides, Alive Directory', '25-best-web-directories-for-seo', 1691, '2015-10-15 21:32:18', 0, 1);
